      <div style="background:#d4b76a;grid-column:7/10;"></div>
      <div style="background:#2d5016;grid-column:10/13;"></div>
    </div>
    <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(4,1fr);font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:0.6rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:0.08em;border-bottom:1px solid var(--sand);">
      <div style="padding:0.5rem 1rem;color:#e63946;">Weeks 1‚Äì4 ¬∑ Healing</div>
      <div style="padding:0.5rem 1rem;color:var(--sage);">Weeks 5‚Äì6 ¬∑ Rooting</div>
      <div style="padding:0.5rem 1rem;color:#92400e;">Weeks 7‚Äì9 ¬∑ CAN Arc</div>
      <div style="padding:0.5rem 1rem;color:var(--moss);">Weeks 10‚Äì12 ¬∑ Leading</div>
    </div>
    <div style="padding:1.25rem 1.5rem;display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fit,minmax(160px,1fr));gap:0.75rem;">
      <div style="font-size:0.8rem;"><strong style="display:block;font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;">Modules I‚ÄìIII</strong><span style="color:#777;font-size:0.75rem;">Identity, Systems, Distress<br>PERMA baseline set</span></div>
      <div style="font-size:0.8rem;"><strong style="display:block;font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;">Modules IV‚ÄìV</strong><span style="color:#777;font-size:0.75rem;">Regulate, Meaning<br>PERMA deepening</span></div>
      <div style="font-size:0.8rem;"><strong style="display:block;font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;color:#92400e;">CAN: Connect ¬∑ Adapt ¬∑ Innovate</strong><span style="color:#777;font-size:0.75rem;">3 dedicated weeks<br>Stanford leadership framework</span></div>
      <div style="font-size:0.8rem;"><strong style="display:block;font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;">Module VI + Capstone</strong><span style="color:#777;font-size:0.75rem;">Agency, Community<br>PERMA endline + graduation</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div style="background:var(--earth);color:white;border-radius:12px;padding:1.75rem;margin-bottom:1rem;">
    <div style="font-family:'DM Mono',monospace;font-size:0.65rem;letter-spacing:0.12em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--fern);margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Why PERMA + CAN together?</div>
    <p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:rgba(255,255,255,0.72);line-height:1.75;max-width:720px;">PERMA asks: <em>what makes a person flourish?</em> CAN asks: <em>what makes a sustainability leader effective?</em> The insight of v3 is that these are the same question at different scales. A person who is flourishing in PERMA terms ‚Äî feeling positive emotions, engaged, connected, purposeful, and accomplished ‚Äî is precisely the person who has the inner resources to Connect, Adapt, and Innovate in complex systems. PERMA builds the foundation; CAN is what you build on it.</p>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê PERMA PAGE ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="perma">
<div class="container">
  <h2 class="page-title">PERMA: The Daily Well-Being Spine</h2>
  <p class="page-sub">Seligman's PERMA framework (Positive Emotion ¬∑ Engagement ¬∑ Relationships ¬∑ Meaning ¬∑ Accomplishment) runs as a <em>daily micro-exercise layer</em> beneath every module. Each element maps directly to the climate resilience context. The PERMA-Profiler is administered at Week 1 (baseline), Week 6 (mid-point), and Week 12 (outcome) ‚Äî providing the primary quantitative outcome measure for the blind study.</p>

  <!-- PERMA tracker demo -->
  <div class="perma-tracker">
    <h3>üå± Your PERMA Climate Snapshot</h3>
    <p>Sample well-being profile ‚Äî updated weekly through Sunnie check-ins (illustrative)</p>
    <div class="perma-bars">
      <div class="perma-row">
        <div class="perma-label"><span class="perma-pill pp">P</span> Positive Emotion</div>
        <div class="perma-track"><div class="perma-fill" style="width:62%;background:var(--p);"></div></div>
        <div class="perma-score">6.2</div>
      </div>
      <div class="perma-row">
        <div class="perma-label"><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span> Engagement</div>
        <div class="perma-track"><div class="perma-fill" style="width:75%;background:var(--e);"></div></div>
        <div class="perma-score">7.5</div>
      </div>
      <div class="perma-row">
        <div class="perma-label"><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span> Relationships</div>
        <div class="perma-track"><div class="perma-fill" style="width:58%;background:var(--r);"></div></div>
        <div class="perma-score">5.8</div>
      </div>
      <div class="perma-row">
        <div class="perma-label"><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span> Meaning</div>
        <div class="perma-track"><div class="perma-fill" style="width:81%;background:var(--m);"></div></div>
        <div class="perma-score">8.1</div>
      </div>
      <div class="perma-row">
        <div class="perma-label"><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span> Accomplishment</div>
        <div class="perma-track"><div class="perma-fill" style="width:48%;background:var(--aa);"></div></div>
        <div class="perma-score">4.8</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="act-grid">
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--p);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">‚òÄÔ∏è</div>
        <div class="act-method"><span class="perma-pill pp">P</span> Positive Emotion ¬∑ Daily 3 min</div>
        <h4>Climate Awe Journal</h4>
        <p>Each morning Sunnie prompts: "Find one moment of awe, beauty, or wonder connected to the living world today ‚Äî however small." Research shows awe specifically counteracts the constricted attention of climate anxiety, broadens perspective, and generates prosocial motivation. Logged daily, reviewed weekly.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Seligman (2011): positive emotions include "joy, gratitude, serenity, interest, hope, pride, amusement, inspiration, awe, and love." Keltner & Haidt (2003): awe uniquely induces small-self effect ‚Äî users feel part of something larger than themselves, directly counteracting climate helplessness.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--e);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåä</div>
        <div class="act-method"><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span> Engagement ¬∑ Daily 5 min</div>
        <h4>Eco-Flow Finder</h4>
        <p>Sunnie asks: "What sustainability-related activity made time disappear this week?" Users identify their eco-flow state ‚Äî the activities where skills and challenge are matched and engagement is total. Then Sunnie helps design 5-minute daily practice around that activity. Flow is both a well-being builder and a reliable indicator of intrinsic motivation.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Seligman (2011): engagement refers to being "fully absorbed, interested, and engaged in life" ‚Äî the flow state. Csikszentmihalyi's flow research shows intrinsic engagement predicts sustained behavior far more than obligation. PMC (2025): intrinsic ecological motivation is the most durable predictor of pro-environmental behavior.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--r);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">ü§ù</div>
        <div class="act-method"><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span> Relationships ¬∑ Weekly 10 min</div>
        <h4>Climate Conversation Card</h4>
        <p>Each week Sunnie generates a "conversation starter card" ‚Äî a question about climate, nature, or the future designed to be shared with one person in the user's life. Not to convince or debate ‚Äî just to connect. Research shows climate conversations deepen relationships, reduce isolation, and normalize eco-emotion. Cards are calibrated for intimacy level (casual ‚Üí close).</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Seligman (2011): "other people matter" ‚Äî relationships are fundamental to all five PERMA elements. Good Grief Network: community and shared vulnerability are core therapeutic mechanisms. PMC (2025): social diffusion of pro-environmental behavior is one of five validated pathways to sustained climate action.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--m);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üß≠</div>
        <div class="act-method"><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span> Meaning ¬∑ Daily 2 min</div>
        <h4>Purpose Pulse</h4>
        <p>A 2-minute end-of-day Sunnie check-in: "Did today feel connected to something larger than yourself? Rate 1‚Äì10 and tell me one sentence why." Tracks meaning over time, flags when it drops, and prompts a "meaning recovery" exercise when scores fall below 5 for 3 consecutive days. Directly tracks the Cambridge Ch.14 meaning-focused coping construct.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Seligman (2011): meaning is "belonging to and serving something that you believe is bigger than the self." Cambridge Ch.14 (Ojala & Chen): meaning-focused coping is the only coping style associated with BOTH better mental health AND higher climate engagement simultaneously.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--aa);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üèÜ</div>
        <div class="act-method"><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span> Accomplishment ¬∑ Weekly</div>
        <h4>Eco-Achievement Log</h4>
        <p>Every Sunday, Sunnie prompts users to log one sustainability-related accomplishment from the week ‚Äî however small (read one article, reduced one plastic, had one climate conversation, completed one module activity). Displayed in a visual timeline. Research shows regular acknowledgment of small wins builds the self-efficacy needed to attempt larger ones.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Seligman (2011): accomplishment includes "making progress toward goals, feeling capable, and a sense of achievement." PMC (2025): self-efficacy ‚Äî the belief that one's actions matter ‚Äî is the strongest predictor of sustained pro-environmental behavior within the PsyCap framework.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--p),var(--e),var(--r),var(--m),var(--aa));"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üìä</div>
        <div class="act-method">All 5 Elements ¬∑ Weekly Synthesis</div>
        <h4>PERMA Climate Check-In</h4>
        <p>Each Sunday, a 5-question Sunnie check-in (one per PERMA element, each scored 0‚Äì10) builds the weekly PERMA profile. Scores are visualized on the radar chart above. When a domain drops significantly, Sunnie offers a targeted "repair" activity for that specific element. At Weeks 1, 6, and 12, the validated PERMA-Profiler (Butler & Kern) is administered for research-grade data collection.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Butler & Kern (2016): the PERMA-Profiler uses 15 validated items (3 per domain) plus 8 filler items for research-grade PERMA measurement. PMC (2025, Qatar study): PERMA is valid in youth populations as a well-being measure, with particular sensitivity to anxiety and depression as negative correlates.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sunnie-wrap">
    <div class="sunnie-head">üí¨ Sunnie ‚Äî Daily PERMA Check-In</div>
    <div class="d-line"><strong>Sunnie (morning):</strong> Good morning. Before the day pulls you in ‚Äî one tiny moment. Is there anything in the natural world near you right now, however small, that you can notice for 30 seconds? A cloud, the light, a plant? <em>[P ‚Äî Awe prompt]</em></div>
    <div class="d-line"><strong>Sunnie (evening):</strong> Quick pulse check ‚Äî how connected did today feel to something larger than yourself? Just a number, 1 to 10. And one word for why. <em>[M ‚Äî Purpose Pulse]</em></div>
    <div class="d-line"><strong>Sunnie (Sunday):</strong> Weekly PERMA check-in time. Five questions, two minutes. Your scores this week go on your climate well-being map ‚Äî so we can see what's building and what might need some attention.</div>
  </div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê MODULE I ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="m1">
  <div class="mod-hero" data-glyph="I" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#2a1a0e,#4a2010);">
    <div class="mod-inner">
      <div class="mod-eyebrow" style="color:var(--clay)">Module I ¬∑ Weeks 1‚Äì2 ¬∑ Stanford Ring: Identity</div>
      <h2>Who Am I in<br><em>Relation to the Earth?</em></h2>
      <p class="mod-rationale">The Stanford "New Leader" model places identity at its center ‚Äî values, purpose, and ecological self. The Cambridge book adds the clinical dimension: climate threatens adolescent identity formation in developmentally specific ways. This module establishes the PERMA baseline and builds the ecological identity that anchors every subsequent module.</p>
      <div class="cite-chips">
        <span class="cc">Novy et al. 2021 ‚Äî Identity Ring</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.3‚Äì4 ‚Äî Youth Identity & Climate</span>
        <span class="cc">PERMA: P + M baseline</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slabel">Core Activities ¬∑ Weeks 1‚Äì2</div>
  <div class="act-grid">
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--ember);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåç</div>
        <div class="act-method">Ecological Identity ¬∑ Narrative ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>The Earth That Made Me</h4>
        <p>Sunnie guides a structured narrative: "Describe a place in nature that shaped who you are. What did it teach you? What does it mean that it's changing?" Activates ecological identity ‚Äî the foundation of both New Leader development and meaning-based coping.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): identity is "their mental model of themselves defined in terms of their values and special purpose." Cambridge Ch.4: climate threatens identity formation ‚Äî naming ecological identity explicitly is a first protective intervention.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--ember);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üß†</div>
        <div class="act-method">Psychoeducation ¬∑ Developmental ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pe">E</span></div>
        <h4>Why Young People Feel This More</h4>
        <p>A Sunnie micro-lesson: young people are developmentally primed to feel climate distress more intensely ‚Äî future orientation, identity, and justice-sensitivity are all heightened in adolescence. Normalizing this removes shame and increases engagement with the curriculum.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.3: "a template for assessing young people's climate emotions clinically" ‚Äî explains how "chronic stress and climate impacts play on child and adolescent brain development." Understanding the neuroscience is itself therapeutic.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--ember);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">ü™û</div>
        <div class="act-method">Values Clarification ¬∑ ACT ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>Ecological Values Map</h4>
        <p>Interactive card-sort of 16 ecological values ‚Äî users rank and select their top 3. These become the identity anchor referenced across all 12 weeks, especially during the CAN arc's Innovate week when values-aligned action is designed.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): New Leaders must be "committed to sustainability and intergenerational well-being" and "grounded in ethics." Values must be surfaced before they can drive sustained action. PERMA: Meaning and Accomplishment both require a clear values anchor.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--ember);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üìä</div>
        <div class="act-method">Assessment ¬∑ Baseline ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>PERMA Baseline + Climate Distress Thermometer</h4>
        <p>Week 1 Day 1: full PERMA-Profiler (15 items, validated) + Climate Distress Thermometer (0‚Äì10 across anxiety, grief, anger, guilt). These are the primary outcome measures for the blind study. Results shown to users as their personalized "starting map."</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Butler & Kern (2016): PERMA-Profiler validated across populations including youth. Lindqvist et al. (2023): climate-specific distress scales are valid outcome measures for ICBT interventions. Baseline measurement is itself therapeutic ‚Äî it names and quantifies what was previously felt but unnamed.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê MODULE II ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="m2">
  <div class="mod-hero" data-glyph="II" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#0e2a1a,#1a4028);">
    <div class="mod-inner">
      <div class="mod-eyebrow" style="color:var(--fern)">Module II ¬∑ Week 3 ¬∑ Stanford Ring: Perspective</div>
      <h2>Seeing the System<br><em>Without Drowning in It</em></h2>
      <p class="mod-rationale">Systems thinking is the Stanford curriculum's Perspective element ‚Äî but the Cambridge CBT chapter shows that systems awareness without emotional scaffolding amplifies distress. This module teaches systems thinking therapeutically, as a tool for finding leverage points and building PERMA Engagement through meaningful intellectual absorption.</p>
      <div class="cite-chips">
        <span class="cc">Novy et al. 2021 ‚Äî ¬ß3.2.1 Systems Perspective</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.8 ‚Äî CBT for Eco-Emotions</span>
        <span class="cc">PERMA: E + M</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slabel">Core Activities ¬∑ Week 3</div>
  <div class="act-grid">
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--moss);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üï∏Ô∏è</div>
        <div class="act-method">Systems Thinking ¬∑ CBT ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>Your Leverage Point Map</h4>
        <p>Map one climate issue: 3 causes, 3 effects, one leverage point where intervention is possible. The psychological goal is the felt experience of finding agency within complexity ‚Äî not comprehensive systems analysis. Engagement is built through intellectual absorption in a real problem.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): systems element cultivates "awareness of the dynamic and interrelated nature of social-environmental systems." Cambridge Ch.8: CBT for eco-emotions involves identifying cognitive distortions ‚Äî especially all-or-nothing thinking ‚Äî that make systems feel sealed to human influence.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--moss);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üì∞</div>
        <div class="act-method">ACT Defusion ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span></div>
        <h4>News as Data, Not Verdict</h4>
        <p>Select one climate news story and practice ACT defusion ‚Äî treating it as information rather than a definitive statement about the future. "What does this story tell us is happening? What does it NOT tell us about what's possible?" Rebuilds positive emotion by restoring epistemic agency.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.5: anxiety activates threat-detection disproportionately. ACT defusion interrupts fusion between news and catastrophic prediction. Seligman (2011): positive emotions include "interest" and "hope" ‚Äî both depend on maintaining interpretive flexibility.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--moss);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üå±</div>
        <div class="act-method">Positive Systems ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>Emergence & Possibility Scan</h4>
        <p>Explore 2‚Äì3 real examples of positive emergence in climate systems (renewable cost curves, rewilding successes, policy breakthroughs). Reflect: "What does this tell you about what's possible in complex systems?" Counteracts linear extrapolation ‚Äî the cognitive distortion most correlated with climate despair.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): New Leaders "see problems as opportunities in disguise." Cambridge Ch.8: behavioral experiments providing disconfirming evidence for catastrophic beliefs are a core CBT technique for climate distress. Positive emotion builds on evidence, not wishful thinking.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--moss);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üîÑ</div>
        <div class="act-method">Uncertainty Tolerance ¬∑ ACT ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>Making Peace with Not Knowing</h4>
        <p>ACT-based exercise: what must be accepted as genuinely unknown vs. what can be acted on despite uncertainty? This directly builds the Stanford capability of "capacity to understand change, be adaptable, embrace ambiguity" ‚Äî through a therapeutic rather than merely intellectual process.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): adaptability and uncertainty tolerance are core New Leader capabilities. Cambridge Ch.10: ACT-informed climate therapy has "increasing the tolerance for uncertainty" as a primary therapeutic goal. PERMA Engagement requires the willingness to stay in the game despite unknown outcomes.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê MODULE III ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="m3">
  <div class="mod-hero" data-glyph="III" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#0e1a2a,#1a2a40);">
    <div class="mod-inner">
      <div class="mod-eyebrow" style="color:#8fb8d4">Module III ¬∑ Week 4 ¬∑ Cambridge Clinical Foundations</div>
      <h2>The Full Spectrum<br><em>of Climate Distress</em></h2>
      <p class="mod-rationale">The Cambridge book's taxonomy ‚Äî psychiatric, developmental, neurobiological, psychoanalytic, trauma, and CBT dimensions ‚Äî is translated into a user-facing map. Users who can locate themselves on a spectrum make better decisions about what kind of support they need. This is also where PERMA scores often dip ‚Äî Sunnie is calibrated to respond therapeutically when they do.</p>
      <div class="cite-chips">
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.3 ‚Äî Psychiatric Perspectives</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.5 ‚Äî Neurobiology</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.6 ‚Äî Psychoanalytic</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.7 ‚Äî Trauma</span>
        <span class="cc">PERMA: R + M repair</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slabel">Core Activities ¬∑ Week 4</div>
  <div class="act-grid">
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:#6a8fa8;"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üó∫Ô∏è</div>
        <div class="act-method">Psychoeducation ¬∑ Assessment ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>The Climate Distress Spectrum</h4>
        <p>Visual spectrum from healthy eco-emotion ‚Üí subclinical distress ‚Üí clinical presentation. Users locate themselves ‚Äî not to diagnose, but to understand what kind of support fits their current state and to destigmatize the full range. Meaning is built through accurate self-understanding.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.3: "describes the spectrum of healthy and unhealthy pediatric anxiety and depression in response to climate change." Self-location on a spectrum is a validated CBT psychoeducation technique that reduces shame and increases help-seeking.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:#6a8fa8;"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üß¨</div>
        <div class="act-method">Neuroscience ¬∑ Psychoeducation ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pe">E</span></div>
        <h4>Your Brain on Climate News</h4>
        <p>Visual explanation of amygdala activation, cortisol loops, and attentional narrowing during climate threat processing. Knowing the biology of their own distress gives users metacognitive distance and reduces secondary fear ("what's wrong with me?"). Engagement is rebuilt through curiosity about one's own neuroscience.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.5 (Neuropsychiatric Perspectives): focuses on "the biology of anxiety and youth climate distress" and how chronic stress affects brain development. Making this visible to users is a core CBT psychoeducation technique.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:#6a8fa8;"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåä</div>
        <div class="act-method">Trauma-Informed ¬∑ DBT ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pr">R</span></div>
        <h4>When Overwhelm Becomes Numbness</h4>
        <p>Addresses climate dissociation ‚Äî emotional shutdown when the scale of threat is too large to process. Sunnie names this, explains it as a trauma-protective mechanism, and offers grounding techniques. Relationships (PERMA R) are often the first casualty of dissociation ‚Äî reconnection is the repair.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.7: "Understanding the Role of Trauma and Dissociation in Youth Responses to Climate Crises" ‚Äî dissociative responses are common and under-addressed. Naming them prevents their misinterpretation as indifference ‚Äî which is one of the most isolating experiences for climate-engaged youth.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:#6a8fa8;"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üîë</div>
        <div class="act-method">Psychoanalytic ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span></div>
        <h4>What Your Climate Feelings Are Protecting</h4>
        <p>"Sometimes anxiety or anger about climate protects something underneath ‚Äî grief, love, a sense of powerlessness. What might yours be protecting?" Builds emotional literacy that allows deeper processing. Meaning and Relationships are both deepened when we can speak honestly about what's underneath.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.6 (Psychoanalytic Perspectives): introduces unconscious dimensions of climate distress ‚Äî surface emotions (anger, anxiety) often protect deeper ones (grief, attachment loss). Integrating this creates psychological depth that CBT alone cannot reach.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê MODULE IV ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="m4">
  <div class="mod-hero" data-glyph="IV" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#0e2a18,#1a4a2a);">
    <div class="mod-inner">
      <div class="mod-eyebrow" style="color:var(--fern)">Module IV ¬∑ Weeks 5‚Äì6 ¬∑ Stanford Ring: Capability</div>
      <h2>Regulate, Root,<br><em>Restore</em></h2>
      <p class="mod-rationale">The Stanford Capability ring and Cambridge Ch.10 (therapist practice) converge here. Clinical interventions ‚Äî ACT, psychodynamic, ecotherapy, creative expression ‚Äî are translated into Flourish activities. PERMA Engagement and Relationships are both deepened through embodied practice and peer connection in Climate Circles.</p>
      <div class="cite-chips">
        <span class="cc">Novy et al. 2021 ‚Äî Capability Ring</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.10 ‚Äî Therapists' Perspectives</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.11 ‚Äî Intersectional</span>
        <span class="cc">PERMA: E + R deepening</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slabel">Core Activities ¬∑ Weeks 5‚Äì6</div>
  <div class="act-grid">
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--sage);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">‚öì</div>
        <div class="act-method">ACT ¬∑ Psychodynamic ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>Secure Base Mapping</h4>
        <p>Cambridge Ch.10 identifies secure attachment as the therapeutic foundation for weathering the climate crisis. Sunnie helps users map their secure bases ‚Äî people, places, practices, and values. These become PERMA Relationship anchors revisited throughout the CAN arc when the work gets harder.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.10: "the importance of providing a secure attachment relationship to use as a base in 'weathering the storms' of the climate crisis is emphasized." Seligman (2011): "other people matter" ‚Äî relationships are the most consistently protective element across all PERMA domains.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--sage);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåø</div>
        <div class="act-method">Ecotherapy ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span></div>
        <h4>Conscious Nature Relationship</h4>
        <p>5-minute daily: intentional sensory observation of one living thing, journaling one thing noticed. Rebuilds the felt sense of belonging to the natural world ‚Äî counteracting the alienation that climate grief produces. Both Positive Emotion (awe) and Engagement (absorption) are generated through genuine nature contact.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.10: "developing a conscious relationship to nature" is explicitly named as a core clinical intervention. Cambridge Ch.11: ecological perspectives argue that healing the human-nature relationship IS the therapeutic goal, not just a means to it.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--sage);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üé≠</div>
        <div class="act-method">Expressive ¬∑ Play-Based ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>Environmental Creative Expression</h4>
        <p>Weekly creative prompt with an environmental theme ‚Äî drawing, writing, music, or storytelling. Processing climate through creative expression reaches affect that verbal processing cannot. Engagement (flow in creative work) and Accomplishment (completing something) are both generated. Available in any format.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.10: "the clinician is encouraged to have and use play materials that can be adapted to environmental themes." Baudon & Jachens (2021): creative expression appears in 26% of eco-anxiety intervention studies as a recommended modality.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--sage);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåê</div>
        <div class="act-method">Intersectional ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>Whose Crisis? Whose Burden?</h4>
        <p>Cambridge Ch.11's intersectional framework: climate distress is not uniformly distributed. Users locate their own position in climate justice, building empathy and intersectional understanding ‚Äî a New Leader competency. Relationships and Meaning are both deepened when justice is made personal.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.11 (Ananda & Babbott): "ecological and intersectional perspectives to reduce young adults' climate distress." Novy et al. (2021): New Leaders must be "highly collaborative and inclusive" and "build bridges" ‚Äî which requires understanding differential burden.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê MODULE V ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="m5">
  <div class="mod-hero" data-glyph="V" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#2a1a0a,#4a3010);">
    <div class="mod-inner">
      <div class="mod-eyebrow" style="color:var(--clay)">Module V ¬∑ Week 6 ¬∑ Cambridge Ch.14: Meaning-Focused Coping</div>
      <h2>From Paralysis<br><em>to Purpose</em></h2>
      <p class="mod-rationale">Ojala & Chen's meaning-focused coping is the empirical bridge between healing and leadership ‚Äî the only coping style associated with BOTH better mental health AND greater climate engagement. PERMA Meaning scores typically peak in this module. This is the pivot point before the CAN arc begins.</p>
      <div class="cite-chips">
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.14 ‚Äî Ojala & Chen</span>
        <span class="cc">ACT Committed Action</span>
        <span class="cc">PERMA: M + A peak</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slabel">Core Activities ¬∑ Week 6 (bridge to CAN)</div>
  <div class="act-grid">
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--clay);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üß≠</div>
        <div class="act-method">Meaning-Focused ¬∑ ACT ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>What Does This Call Me Toward?</h4>
        <p>The core meaning-focused exercise. Sunnie: "Looking at your ecological values map ‚Äî what does your care want to do? Not what should you do. What does your love of the Earth want to do?" The distinction from guilt-based action is made explicit. This question becomes the seed for the CAN arc's Innovate week.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.14 (Ojala & Chen): "meaning-focused coping and constructive hope are interrelated and both associated with mental well-being and climate engagement." ACT: committed action emerges from values, not obligation.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--clay);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåÖ</div>
        <div class="act-method">Constructive Hope ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span></div>
        <h4>Hope as Practice, Not Feeling</h4>
        <p>Constructive hope (Ojala): evidence-based, action-oriented, compatible with grief. One climate win per week + one action taken, however small. "Research with young activists shows they didn't feel hopeful and then engage ‚Äî they engaged, and then felt hope." PERMA Positive Emotion is rebuilt through evidence, not wishful thinking.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.14: "collective climate engagement can give hope and meaning to young activists" ‚Äî hope is an output of action, not a prerequisite. Ojala's empirical work shows constructive hope mediates the relationship between climate worry and pro-environmental behavior.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--clay);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üìä</div>
        <div class="act-method">Assessment ¬∑ Mid-point ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>Week 6 PERMA-Profiler + Mid-Point Review</h4>
        <p>Full PERMA-Profiler re-administration at Week 6. Results compared to Week 1 baseline ‚Äî shown to user as a personalized progress map. Sunnie discusses what's shifted and what needs more attention in the CAN arc. Mid-point data collection for the blind study.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Lindqvist et al. (2023): mid-point measurement in ICBT trials helps identify non-responders early, allowing protocol adjustment. Mid-point PERMA scores are expected to show gains in M and R, with P and A typically lagging until the CAN arc (Weeks 7‚Äì9) generates concrete accomplishment experiences.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--clay);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üõë</div>
        <div class="act-method">Burnout Prevention ¬∑ ACT ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>Activism Balance Sheet</h4>
        <p>Cambridge Appendix B: Costs and Benefits of Activism Scale ‚Äî honestly weighing the costs (time, emotional labor, social friction) against the benefits (meaning, community, hope). This calibration prevents both under-engagement (paralysis) and over-commitment (burnout) before the more demanding CAN arc begins.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Appendix B: validated clinical tool for helping climate-engaged youth calibrate sustainable involvement. Terrien & Brouillard (2024): ACT cultivates "psychological self-care that prevents climate fatigue or burnout" ‚Äî essential before the Innovate week asks for real-world commitment.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê CAN FRAMEWORK ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="can">
  <div class="can-hero">
    <div class="can-inner">
      <div class="can-eyebrow">Stanford CAN Framework ¬∑ Weeks 7‚Äì9 ¬∑ The Action Arc</div>
      <h2>Connect. Adapt. <em>Innovate.</em></h2>
      <p class="can-desc">Julia Novy's CAN framework ‚Äî taught in Stanford's SUST 220 and named explicitly in her sustainability leadership research ‚Äî identifies three orientations of effective sustainability leaders. In v3, CAN becomes a dedicated 3-week immersive arc: one full week per orientation, with daily practices, a major weekly challenge, and PERMA tracking throughout. This is where inner work becomes outer movement.</p>
      <div class="cite-chips">
        <span class="cc">Novy-Hildesley, SUST 220, Stanford 2021</span>
        <span class="cc">Novy, Banerjee & Matson, MDPI 2021 ‚Äî ¬ß3.2.2</span>
        <span class="cc">Stanford GSB Sustainability Conference 2024</span>
        <span class="cc">PERMA: all 5 elements activated</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="can-three">
    <div class="can-col">
      <div class="can-col-header">
        <div class="can-letter" style="background:var(--can-c);">C</div>
        <div><h3>Connect</h3><div class="can-sub">Week 7</div></div>
      </div>
      <p>Build bridges across difference. Connect with those who hold different perspectives, positions, and power. The New Leader must be "highly collaborative and inclusive" and capable of "deep listening, empathy, and inquiry." This week: radical listening, stakeholder mapping, and finding shared values beneath conflict.</p>
      <span class="can-week-tag" style="background:rgba(37,99,235,0.15);color:#93c5fd;">Weeks 7 ¬∑ PERMA: R + P</span>
    </div>
    <div class="can-col">
      <div class="can-col-header">
        <div class="can-letter" style="background:var(--can-a);">A</div>
        <div><h3>Adapt</h3><div class="can-sub">Week 8</div></div>
      </div>
      <p>Embrace uncertainty, iterate, pivot. The New Leader has "capacity to understand change, be adaptable, embrace ambiguity." This week: design thinking methodology, rapid prototyping mindset, learning from failure, and building resilience reservoirs that enable sustained engagement despite setbacks.</p>
      <span class="can-week-tag" style="background:rgba(124,58,237,0.15);color:#c4b5fd;">Week 8 ¬∑ PERMA: E + A</span>
    </div>
    <div class="can-col">
      <div class="can-col-header">
        <div class="can-letter" style="background:var(--can-i);">I</div>
        <div><h3>Innovate</h3><div class="can-sub">Week 9</div></div>
      </div>
      <p>Create new possibilities. "Creative confidence in the face of daunting challenges, risk-taking, bias for action." This week: design a values-aligned innovation ‚Äî however small ‚Äî using the user's ecological identity (Module I), leverage point (Module II), and meaningful action (Module V) as raw material.</p>
      <span class="can-week-tag" style="background:rgba(217,119,6,0.15);color:#fcd34d;">Week 9 ¬∑ PERMA: M + A peak</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- CONNECT ACTIVITIES -->
  <div class="slabel" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">Week 7 ¬∑ CONNECT</div>
  <div class="can-act-grid">
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-c);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üëÇ</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#2563eb;"><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span> Empathy Interviewing ¬∑ Stanford Design Thinking</div>
        <h4>The Radical Listening Challenge</h4>
        <p>Sunnie introduces Stanford design thinking's "empathy interview" method ‚Äî then challenges users to conduct one 20-minute conversation with someone who holds a different perspective on climate (a farmer, a skeptic, an elder, a child). The goal is not to persuade ‚Äî it's to understand. Users report back: what surprised them?</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): the Stanford curriculum used "empathy interviews to engage over 100 leaders" as its primary design methodology. New Leaders require "deep listening, empathy, and inquiry capability." PERMA R: quality relationships are built through genuine curiosity, not through agreement.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-c);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåâ</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#2563eb;"><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span> Multi-Stakeholder Mapping</div>
        <h4>Who Else Is In This System?</h4>
        <p>Using the leverage point map from Module II, users identify 5‚Äì8 stakeholders with different relationships to their chosen climate issue. For each: what do they value? What do they fear? Where do their values overlap with yours? This map becomes the foundation for the Innovate week's partnership design.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): New Leaders must "build bridges and span silos to partner with diverse stakeholders." Cambridge Ch.15: social-ecological systems framework shows that protective factors against climate distress operate at multiple system levels ‚Äî requiring multi-stakeholder literacy.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-c);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üî•</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#2563eb;"><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span> Climate Circle Deep Dive</div>
        <h4>Peer Witnessing Session</h4>
        <p>Week 7's Climate Circle session uses structured peer witnessing: each member shares their leverage point and one honest fear about acting on it. Others witness without advice. Research shows being witnessed ‚Äî not helped ‚Äî is one of the most therapeutically potent experiences available. Radical connection in 30 minutes.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Good Grief Network: peer witnessing in small groups (capped at 15) is the therapeutic mechanism at the heart of their model. Cambridge Ch.15: peer relationships at the meso-system level are the most consistently protective factor against youth climate distress.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ADAPT ACTIVITIES -->
  <div class="slabel">Week 8 ¬∑ ADAPT</div>
  <div class="can-act-grid">
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-a);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üîÅ</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#7c3aed;"><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span> Design Thinking ¬∑ Rapid Prototype</div>
        <h4>Fail Forward Challenge</h4>
        <p>Sunnie introduces design thinking's "bias toward action" principle. Users identify one climate-related micro-experiment they can run this week ‚Äî something small enough to do but meaningful enough to learn from. They run it, report back, and Sunnie helps them extract the learning. Normalizes iteration over perfection.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): curriculum core element 3 uses "iterative rapid prototyping" and "decision making in complex scenarios." Stanford's design thinking methodology explicitly teaches that failure is data, not defeat. PERMA Engagement peaks in flow states ‚Äî rapid prototyping generates these.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-a);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üß©</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#7c3aed;"><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span> Scenario Planning ¬∑ Futures Thinking</div>
        <h4>Three Futures Exercise</h4>
        <p>Sunnie guides a simplified scenario planning exercise: users map three plausible 10-year futures for their chosen issue (pessimistic, business-as-usual, transformative). Then ask: what would need to be true for the transformative scenario? What small things could nudge toward it? Builds adaptive foresight ‚Äî seeing possibility space in uncertainty.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): the Stanford curriculum includes "scenario planning" as a core decision-making tool. "Effective decision making, drawing on foresight and pattern recognition" is a named New Leader capability. PERMA Meaning is deepened when users can locate their actions within a larger possible story.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-a);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üîã</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#7c3aed;"><span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span> Resilience Reservoir</div>
        <h4>What Refills Your Tank?</h4>
        <p>Visual reservoir metaphor: users log what fills their resilience (sleep, nature, community, creativity, rest) vs. what drains it (doom-scrolling, overcommitment, isolation). Maps their sustainable engagement capacity. Sunnie monitors reservoir levels across the CAN arc and flags depletion before burnout sets in.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): "personal resilience and capacity to build resilience across scales" is a named New Leader attribute. PMC (2025): resilience within the PsyCap framework is one of four validated predictors of reduced climate anxiety. PERMA Positive Emotion is first to decline when the reservoir is empty.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- INNOVATE ACTIVITIES -->
  <div class="slabel">Week 9 ¬∑ INNOVATE</div>
  <div class="can-act-grid">
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-i);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üí°</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#d97706;"><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span> Systems Innovation ¬∑ Design</div>
        <h4>Your Climate Innovation Brief</h4>
        <p>The capstone of the CAN arc. Using their ecological values (Module I), leverage point (Module II), stakeholder map (Connect), and scenario planning (Adapt), users design one climate innovation ‚Äî a product, program, campaign, conversation series, or community initiative. It must be specific, values-aligned, and achievable within their current capacity. Sunnie helps scope it realistically.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): curriculum element 3 covers "identifying optimal solutions in contexts with competing objectives" using "project-based learning and co-creation with real-world stakeholders." PERMA Accomplishment peaks when users complete something real that connects to their values.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-i);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üé§</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#d97706;"><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span> Strategic Communications</div>
        <h4>Pitch Your Innovation</h4>
        <p>Sunnie teaches the Stanford curriculum's "strategic communications and storytelling" competency. Users craft a 3-minute pitch for their climate innovation ‚Äî audience: their Climate Circle. Not to be perfect, but to practice the leadership act of making an idea legible and compelling to others. Peer feedback collected.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): stakeholders consistently named "strategic communications and storytelling" as a core New Leader capability. The ability to translate a complex idea into a compelling narrative is one of the most leverage-rich skills a sustainability leader can develop.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="can-act">
      <div class="can-act-top" style="background:var(--can-i);"></div>
      <div class="can-act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåç</div>
        <div class="can-method" style="color:#d97706;"><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span> First Step Commitment</div>
        <h4>The One Real Thing</h4>
        <p>The CAN arc closes with a concrete, public (to their Climate Circle) commitment: the ONE first step they will take on their innovation within 30 days. Not a goal ‚Äî a specific action with a date. Sunnie follows up at Day 15 and Day 30. Social commitment + values alignment + peer accountability = the highest-efficacy action formula in the literature.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): Agency ring ‚Äî "the directionality and nature of their actions allows them to create enabling environments for others to contribute." Cambridge Ch.14 (Ojala): youth activists report that the first concrete action generates the hope that sustains all future actions. Social commitment amplifies follow-through.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sunnie-wrap">
    <div class="sunnie-head">üí¨ Sunnie ‚Äî Across the CAN Arc</div>
    <div class="d-line"><strong>Sunnie (Week 7 ‚Äî Connect):</strong> This week I want you to do something that might feel uncomfortable: have a real conversation with someone who sees climate differently from you. Not to change their mind. Just to understand it. What you learn might surprise you ‚Äî and it'll almost certainly make you a better leader.</div>
    <div class="d-line"><strong>Sunnie (Week 8 ‚Äî Adapt):</strong> Here's something the best innovators know: the first version of anything is supposed to be wrong. This week we're running a micro-experiment ‚Äî small enough to do, meaningful enough to learn from. Failing fast is the strategy, not the failure.</div>
    <div class="d-line"><strong>Sunnie (Week 9 ‚Äî Innovate):</strong> You've spent nine weeks building something. Your values. Your leverage point. Your connections. Your resilience. Now I want to ask you: what do all of those want to create? Not what you think you should do. What does everything you've built actually point toward?</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê MODULE VI ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="m6">
  <div class="mod-hero" data-glyph="VI" style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,#0a1a0a,#162816);">
    <div class="mod-inner">
      <div class="mod-eyebrow" style="color:var(--mist)">Module VI ¬∑ Weeks 10‚Äì12 ¬∑ Stanford Ring: Agency + Cambridge Ch.15</div>
      <h2>Leading Change in<br><em>Complex Systems</em></h2>
      <p class="mod-rationale">Agency is the Stanford curriculum's outermost ring ‚Äî where identity, perspective, and capability become directed action in the world. The Cambridge social-ecological chapter grounds this in multi-system reality: individual resilience alone is insufficient; users must understand and engage the micro-to-macro systems they inhabit. This is also where the PERMA endline is administered.</p>
      <div class="cite-chips">
        <span class="cc">Novy et al. 2021 ‚Äî Agency Ring + ¬ß3.2.2‚Äì3</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.15 ‚Äî Social-Ecological</span>
        <span class="cc">Cambridge Ch.16 ‚Äî Intergenerational</span>
        <span class="cc">PERMA: all 5 endline</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="slabel">Core Activities ¬∑ Weeks 10‚Äì12</div>
  <div class="act-grid">
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--earth);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üåê</div>
        <div class="act-method">Social-Ecological ¬∑ Agency ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span></div>
        <h4>Sphere of Systems Influence</h4>
        <p>Cambridge Ch.15's micro-to-macro framework: users map which systems (family, school/work, community, policy, culture) they already inhabit and have influence within. This becomes their strategic map for deploying the innovation they designed in the Innovate week ‚Äî locating where their action has the most leverage.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Cambridge Ch.15: social-ecological framework spanning micro through macro identifies both risk factors and protective factors against youth climate distress. Novy et al. (2021): Agency involves "the capacity to spur collaboration toward a shared goal" ‚Äî which requires knowing which systems you're in.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--earth);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üî•</div>
        <div class="act-method">Peer Community ¬∑ Climate Circles ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>Climate Circle: Innovation Reviews</h4>
        <p>Week 10 Climate Circle session: each member shares the first-step update from their CAN Innovate commitment. What happened? What did they learn? Peer celebration of actual action taken ‚Äî regardless of outcome. The PERMA Accomplishment element peaks when achievements are witnessed and celebrated by others.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Seligman (2011): "accomplishments can activate other elements of PERMA, such as pride, under positive emotion." Cambridge Ch.15: peer relationships are the most consistently protective factor. Good Grief Network: peer witnessing of action taken is one of their most powerful therapeutic moments.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--earth);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üìä</div>
        <div class="act-method">Assessment ¬∑ Endline ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pp">P</span><span class="perma-pill pe">E</span><span class="perma-pill pr">R</span><span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>Week 12 PERMA-Profiler + Full Outcome Review</h4>
        <p>Full PERMA-Profiler re-administration. Climate Distress Thermometer repeat. Users see their full 12-week PERMA trajectory ‚Äî all five elements graphed from Week 1 through Week 12. Sunnie provides a personalized narrative of what shifted and why. This is the primary outcome data for the blind study.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Lindqvist et al. (2023): 8-week ICBT showed lasting effects across depression (d=0.87), stress (d=0.76), and quality of life (d=0.79). Prediction for this 12-week protocol: largest gains in M (meaning) and R (relationships); P and A gains concentrated in Weeks 9‚Äì12 following the CAN arc's concrete action phase.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="act-card">
      <div class="act-top" style="background:var(--earth);"></div>
      <div class="act-body">
        <div class="act-icon">üå≥</div>
        <div class="act-method">Intergenerational ¬∑ Capstone ¬∑ <span class="perma-pill pm">M</span><span class="perma-pill pa">A</span></div>
        <h4>Letter to the Generation After Mine</h4>
        <p>The closing exercise. Users write a letter to a hypothetical young person 20 years from now ‚Äî describing what they did, what they learned, what they hope that person inherits. Activates the intergenerational stewardship identity that is the explicit normative goal of the Stanford curriculum and completes the meaning arc.</p>
        <div class="act-cite">Novy et al. (2021): "explicit normative goal of intergenerational well-being" is the heart of the Stanford program. Cambridge Ch.16 (Parenting & Grandparenting): intergenerational transmission of both climate anxiety and climate resilience is a key finding ‚Äî writing to the next generation creates a positive transmission loop.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

