<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê BLIND STUDY ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="study">
  <div class="study-hero">
    <div class="study-inner">
      <div class="study-eyebrow">üî¨ Research Design ¬∑ Randomized Controlled Trial</div>
      <h2 style="font-family:'Playfair Display',serif;font-size:clamp(1.5rem,3.5vw,2.4rem);font-weight:900;line-height:1.15;margin-bottom:1rem;color:white;">Designing the<br><em style="font-style:italic;color:#90b4ff;">Blind Study</em></h2>
      <p class="study-desc">How would we rigorously test whether this curriculum actually works? A randomized double-blind controlled trial is the gold standard ‚Äî here is how we would design one for Flourish.ai's climate resilience module, including participant recruitment, randomization, blinding, measures, and ethical considerations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Study design cards -->
  <div class="study-grid">
    <div class="study-card" style="border-top-color:#90b4ff;">
      <h4>Study Design Overview</h4>
      <p>A <strong>parallel-group randomized controlled trial (RCT)</strong> with two arms: intervention (full 12-week curriculum) and active control (general Flourish app use without climate module). Assessors blinded to group assignment. Users not told which arm they're in ‚Äî both receive a "personalized well-being journey."</p>
      <ul>
        <li>N = 200 (100 per arm)</li>
        <li>Duration: 12 weeks + 3-month follow-up</li>
        <li>Design: Parallel RCT, assessor-blinded</li>
        <li>Registration: ClinicalTrials.gov pre-registration</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="study-card" style="border-top-color:#34d399;">
      <h4>Participant Recruitment</h4>
      <p>Target: <strong>young people aged 16‚Äì28</strong> who report moderate or higher climate concern. Recruited via Flourish app onboarding (climate concern screener), university partnerships, and climate-engaged social networks.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Inclusion: ages 16‚Äì28, smartphone access, moderate+ climate concern (score ‚â•4/10)</li>
        <li>Exclusion: current psychotherapy for climate distress, active suicidal ideation</li>
        <li>Stratified randomization by age (16‚Äì21 vs 22‚Äì28), gender, and baseline PERMA score</li>
        <li>Diversity target: ‚â•40% BIPOC, ‚â•30% Global South</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="study-card" style="border-top-color:#f59e0b;">
      <h4>The Blinding Strategy</h4>
      <p>True double-blinding is impossible (users know if they're doing climate content). We use <strong>partial/assessor blinding</strong> ‚Äî the strongest feasible design for a behavioral intervention:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Users:</strong> told they're in one of two "personalized well-being programs" ‚Äî not told which is the climate module</li>
        <li><strong>Assessors:</strong> fully blinded ‚Äî outcome measures administered by researchers with no access to group assignment</li>
        <li><strong>Sunnie:</strong> identical interface in both arms ‚Äî control group Sunnie does not reference climate</li>
        <li><strong>Analysis:</strong> intention-to-treat (ITT), blind to group until analysis complete</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="study-card" style="border-top-color:#e63946;">
      <h4>Control Arm Design</h4>
      <p>The control arm receives Flourish's existing evidence-based content ‚Äî CBT, ACT, PERMA micro-exercises, mindfulness ‚Äî but without the climate frame. This tests whether the <em>climate-specific</em> components add value above and beyond general positive psychology. Both arms receive equal "dose" of app time.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Same daily micro-practice structure (5‚Äì8 min)</li>
        <li>Same PERMA weekly check-ins</li>
        <li>Same Sunnie interaction cadence</li>
        <li>No CAN arc, no ecological identity work, no climate distress content</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="study-card" style="border-top-color:#7c3aed;">
      <h4>Ethical Considerations</h4>
      <p>Climate distress research with minors requires careful ethical scaffolding:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>IRB:</strong> Full IRB review required; separate parental consent protocol for under-18s</li>
        <li><strong>Safety monitoring:</strong> Sunnie monitors for clinical-level distress in both arms; automatic escalation protocol if PHQ-9 or GAD-7 scores indicate clinical need</li>
        <li><strong>Debriefing:</strong> Post-study, control participants offered the full climate curriculum</li>
        <li><strong>Data:</strong> De-identified, GDPR/HIPAA compliant, 5-year retention maximum</li>
        <li><strong>Withdrawals:</strong> Right to withdraw without consequence at any time</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="study-card" style="border-top-color:#2d6a4f;">
      <h4>Follow-Up Protocol</h4>
      <p>One of the weaknesses of existing eco-anxiety studies (including Lindqvist et al.) is short follow-up. This study includes a <strong>3-month follow-up assessment</strong> to test maintenance of gains:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Week 12: endline (primary outcome)</li>
        <li>Week 24 (Month 6): follow-up ‚Äî full PERMA + Climate Distress Thermometer</li>
        <li>Pro-environmental behavior diary: 2-week diary at baseline, Week 12, and Week 24</li>
        <li>Hypothesis: CAN arc's concrete action commitment (One Real Thing) will predict PERMA Accomplishment at Week 24 above and beyond Week 12 scores</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Primary Measures Table -->
  <div class="slabel">Primary & Secondary Outcome Measures</div>
  <table class="measures-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Measure</th>
        <th>Construct</th>
        <th>Timepoints</th>
        <th>Validated?</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>PERMA-Profiler</strong> (Butler & Kern, 2016)</td>
        <td>Overall psychological well-being (5 domains)</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 6, 12, 24</td>
        <td>‚úÖ Validated, youth-appropriate</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Climate Distress Thermometer</strong></td>
        <td>Eco-anxiety, grief, anger, guilt (0‚Äì10 each)</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 6, 12, 24</td>
        <td>‚úÖ Adapted from Lindqvist et al.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>PHQ-9</strong></td>
        <td>Depression severity (safety monitoring)</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 4, 8, 12, 24</td>
        <td>‚úÖ Gold standard</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>GAD-7</strong></td>
        <td>Generalized anxiety severity (safety)</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 4, 8, 12, 24</td>
        <td>‚úÖ Gold standard</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Pro-Environmental Behavior Diary</strong></td>
        <td>Actual climate actions taken (self-report)</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 12, 24 (2-week diary)</td>
        <td>‚úÖ Adapted from Whitmarsh et al.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>CAN Self-Efficacy Scale</strong> (designed for this study)</td>
        <td>Perceived capacity to Connect, Adapt, Innovate</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 7, 9, 12, 24</td>
        <td>‚ö° New ‚Äî requires validation</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Costs & Benefits of Activism Scale</strong> (Cambridge Appendix B)</td>
        <td>Perceived sustainable engagement capacity</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 6, 12</td>
        <td>‚úÖ Cambridge validated</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Ecological Identity Scale</strong></td>
        <td>Sense of self in relation to the natural world</td>
        <td>Wk 1, 12</td>
        <td>‚úÖ Schultz (2002) INS scale</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- Study design phases -->
  <div class="study-design-box">
    <h3>üìã Study Phases</h3>
    <div class="study-phase">
      <div class="study-phase-num">1</div>
      <div class="study-phase-body">
        <h5>Pre-Registration & Protocol (Months 1‚Äì2)</h5>
        <p>Pre-register on ClinicalTrials.gov. IRB approval. Finalize randomization algorithm. Train Sunnie on both intervention and control protocols. Pilot test with 10 users per arm for UX and safety.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="study-phase">
      <div class="study-phase-num">2</div>
      <div class="study-phase-body">
        <h5>Recruitment & Baseline (Month 3)</h5>
        <p>Open recruitment via Flourish app climate screener. Stratified randomization. Week 1 PERMA-Profiler, Climate Distress Thermometer, PHQ-9, GAD-7, Ecological Identity Scale administered. Allocation concealment maintained ‚Äî participants told they're starting a "personalized well-being journey."</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="study-phase">
      <div class="study-phase-num">3</div>
      <div class="study-phase-body">
        <h5>Intervention Period (Months 3‚Äì6)</h5>
        <p>12-week curriculum runs. Weekly PERMA check-ins collected. PHQ-9/GAD-7 safety monitoring at Weeks 4 and 8. Mid-point PERMA-Profiler at Week 6. Fidelity monitoring: Sunnie logs engagement rates, completion of each module activity, and departure from protocol.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="study-phase">
      <div class="study-phase-num">4</div>
      <div class="study-phase-body">
        <h5>Endline & Unblinding (Month 7)</h5>
        <p>Week 12 full outcome assessment. Assessors remain blinded. Data locked. Unblinding occurs only after all Week 12 data is entered and cleaned. Intent-to-treat analysis with multiple imputation for missing data. Effect sizes calculated for all primary outcomes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="study-phase">
      <div class="study-phase-num">5</div>
      <div class="study-phase-body">
        <h5>Follow-Up & Publication (Months 9‚Äì15)</h5>
        <p>Week 24 follow-up assessment. Control arm offered full climate curriculum (ethical obligation). Analysis of follow-up data. Pre-registered primary analysis published regardless of outcome. Secondary analyses (CAN self-efficacy, ecological identity, PEB diary) published separately.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sunnie-wrap" style="background:#0a0a1e;">
    <div class="sunnie-head" style="color:#90b4ff;">üî¨ Key Hypotheses</div>
    <div class="d-line" style="border-left-color:#90b4ff;"><strong style="color:#90b4ff;">H1 (Primary):</strong> Intervention arm will show significantly greater improvement in PERMA total score from Week 1 to Week 12 compared to control (expected d ‚â• 0.5).</div>
    <div class="d-line" style="border-left-color:#90b4ff;"><strong style="color:#90b4ff;">H2:</strong> Climate Distress Thermometer scores will decrease significantly more in the intervention arm (expected d ‚â• 0.6, based on Lindqvist et al. effect sizes).</div>
    <div class="d-line" style="border-left-color:#90b4ff;"><strong style="color:#90b4ff;">H3:</strong> Pro-environmental behavior diary scores at Week 12 will be significantly higher in the intervention arm ‚Äî testing whether treating distress unlocks action (Cambridge Ch.14).</div>
    <div class="d-line" style="border-left-color:#90b4ff;"><strong style="color:#90b4ff;">H4 (CAN-specific):</strong> CAN Self-Efficacy Scale scores will mediate the relationship between curriculum completion and PERMA Accomplishment at Week 24 ‚Äî testing whether the CAN arc's leadership development is the active ingredient for long-term gains.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ‚ïê‚ïê EVIDENCE ‚ïê‚ïê -->
<div class="page" id="evidence">
<div class="container">
  <h2 class="page-title">Evidence Base</h2>
  <p class="page-sub">All activities are traceable to peer-reviewed research. Primary sources anchor the architecture; supporting sources cross-validate specific activities.</p>
  <div class="ev-wrap" style="padding:0;">

    <div class="ev-card" style="border-left-color:var(--ember);">
      <div class="ev-type" style="color:var(--ember);">Primary ¬∑ Stanford ¬∑ MDPI Sustainability 2021</div>
      <h4>Novy, Banerjee & Matson ‚Äî "A Core Curriculum for Sustainability Leadership"</h4>
      <p>Foundational curriculum paper for Stanford's Change Leadership for Sustainability Program. Introduces the New Leader four-ring model (Identity ‚Üí Perspective ‚Üí Capability ‚Üí Agency) and identifies CAN (Connect, Adapt, Innovate) as the three core leadership orientations taught in SUST 220. The paper's explicit normative goal of "intergenerational well-being" becomes the capstone of Module VI. Three curriculum elements map directly to Modules II, V, and the CAN arc.</p>
      <div class="ev-used">Scaffolding for: all modules. CAN arc primary source. Blind study CAN Self-Efficacy Scale design.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="ev-card" style="border-left-color:var(--sage);">
      <div class="ev-type" style="color:var(--sage);">Primary ¬∑ Cambridge University Press 2024</div>
      <h4>Haase & Hudson (eds.) ‚Äî "Climate Change and Youth Mental Health"</h4>
      <p>Most comprehensive clinical text on youth climate distress. Ch.3‚Äì8 provide clinical taxonomy (psychiatric, developmental, neurobiological, psychoanalytic, trauma, CBT). Ch.10 provides therapist practice framework (ACT, psychodynamic, ecotherapy). Ch.11 adds intersectional perspectives. Ch.14 (Ojala & Chen) provides the meaning-focused coping evidence base. Ch.15 provides the social-ecological systems framework. Appendix B (Costs and Benefits of Activism Scale) integrated into Module V and the blind study measures.</p>
      <div class="ev-used">Clinical backbone for all modules. Blind study safety monitoring protocol.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="ev-card" style="border-left-color:#6a8fa8;">
      <div class="ev-type" style="color:#6a8fa8);">Primary ¬∑ Positive Psychology 2011</div>
      <h4>Seligman, M.E.P. ‚Äî "Flourish: A Visionary New Understanding of Happiness and Well-being"</h4>
      <p>Introduces the PERMA model ‚Äî Positive Emotion, Engagement, Relationships, Meaning, Accomplishment ‚Äî as a framework for well-being. Explicitly not a theory but a "listing of phenomena shown to be related to well-being." Each PERMA element is operationalized into a daily micro-exercise in this curriculum. PERMA-Profiler (Butler & Kern, 2016) used for measurement. Notably, the Flourish app takes its name from Seligman's framework ‚Äî this curriculum deepens that alignment.</p>
      <div class="ev-used">Daily micro-exercise layer. Primary outcome measure for blind study.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="ev-card" style="border-left-color:var(--clay);">
      <div class="ev-type" style="color:var(--clay);">Supporting ¬∑ ScienceDirect 2023</div>
      <h4>Lindqvist et al. ‚Äî Climate-Specific ICBT Randomized Controlled Trial</h4>
      <p>The only published RCT on internet-delivered CBT for climate distress. Effect sizes: depression d=0.87, stress d=0.76, quality of life d=0.79 over 8 weeks. ICBT group also showed increased pro-environmental behavior. Validates Flourish's ICBT delivery model and provides effect size benchmarks for the blind study power calculation.</p>
      <div class="ev-used">Blind study benchmark. Power calculation basis. Delivery model validation.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="ev-card" style="border-left-color:var(--moss);">
      <div class="ev-type" style="color:var(--moss);">Supporting ¬∑ PMC 2021</div>
      <h4>Baudon & Jachens ‚Äî Scoping Review of Eco-Anxiety Interventions</h4>
      <p>Reviews 34 records. Five major intervention categories: resilience-building, action-encouraging, social connection, nature connection, grief-informed approaches. Creative expression, grief rituals, and group peer support are evidence-supported. Cross-validates multiple module activities across Modules I, III, IV, and VI.</p>
      <div class="ev-used">Cross-validation for Modules I, III, IV, VI.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="ev-card" style="border-left-color:#8fb8d4;">
      <div class="ev-type" style="color:#8fb8d4;">Supporting ¬∑ PMC 2024</div>
      <h4>PMC (Qatar Study) ‚Äî PERMA in Youth Populations</h4>
      <p>502 high school students. Validates the PERMA-Profiler for use with young people (ages 13‚Äì18). Finds SES and academic performance positively associated with PERMA scores; anxiety and depression negatively associated. Confirms PERMA as appropriate outcome measure for this curriculum's youth target population.</p>
      <div class="ev-used">Blind study measurement validation for youth participants.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="ev-card" style="border-left-color:var(--ember);">
      <div class="ev-type" style="color:var(--ember);">Supporting ¬∑ Taylor & Francis 2024</div>
      <h4>Terrien & Brouillard ‚Äî ACT for Climate-Induced Psychological Distress</h4>
      <p>Establishes ACT's six core processes as directly applicable to eco-anxiety. ACT cultivates "experiential acceptance and mindfulness to focus on psychological self-care that prevents climate fatigue or burnout." Validates ACT defusion (Module II), values clarification (Module I), and committed action (Module V and CAN Innovate) as appropriate for climate distress.</p>
      <div class="ev-used">ACT activities in Modules I, II, V, CAN arc.</div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>
</div>

